<a href="showthread.php?postid=22381#post22381"><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Post #74</font></a><br>
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >Registered: May 2003<br>
	Posts: 25<br><br>



	Server: <br>





                Guild: <br>



<br>	
</td>
	<td bgcolor="#000000" width="100%" valign="top">
	<font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" > <b>Re: a theory</b></font>
	<p><font face="verdana, arial, helvetica" size="2" ><blockquote><font face="verdana,arial,helvetica" size="1" >quote:</font><hr><i>Originally posted by kaledan </i><br />
<b>One thing that coud explain these tests is if:<br />
<br />
AGGRO = HATE + BONUS </b><hr></blockquote> <br />
<br />
That's making a lot of sense.<br />
<br />
In his tests, Brutul is (quite correctly) focusing purely on Taunt.  However, I'd agree that the Hate list is definitely not the only factor in which target a critter will select; it's merely one factor in a behaviour algorithm which also includes proximity and low hp aggro, target invulnerability, and possibly several other factors as well.<br />
<br />
Taunt might well put the warrior at the top of the Hate list; but, I theorise that critters show a tendency to continue to attack their most recent target if the amount of Hate is within a few points.<br />
<br />
<b>Suggested experiment to test this:-</b><br />
<br />
Have the cleric act as before to gain aggro, then the warrior taunts until there is one successful taunt message.  The cleric then hits DA and goes invulnerable.<br />
<br />
The subject will certainly attack the warrior.  What interests me is what will happen when DA wears off... if we're just dealing with a tendency to attack the most recent target when the hate lists are roughly equal, then the subject will stay on the warrior even after DA expires.  If we're dealing with an overall taunt cap, then it will switch back to the cleric.<br />
<br />
Second theory:  Where the hate lists are roughly equal, critters show a tendency to attack whatever has hit them most recently.<br />
<br />
<b>Suggested experiment to test this:-</b><br />
<br />
Have the warrior taunt until one successful taunt indicator, and then kick the critter once.  See if the kick causes it to switch targets without any more taunts.<br />
<br />
Curse you Brutul, you've got me wanting to test this myself :P</font></p>
	
	<p></p>
